So good! Time consuming but definitely worth the effort. I LOVE this cake! A few adjustments that might be helpful: I do not have 10x15 pans so I used regular 9x13 pans. I cooked each layer for an extra 2-5 minutes to allow for the difference in thickness. As for the meringue layers make sure you spread it evenly. The cake and souffle layers were more forgiving and evened out on their own, but the meringue will bake just the way you spread it. Don't skip the buttercream. It was my first time doing this and it still came together perfectly! It only took about 15 minutes in total for my sugar to come to the soft ball stage so keep an eye on it. Make this!

Rating: 0
Not rating this yet... (I will be making this for christmas... I will rate it then). A bit of advice on the buttercreams though... if you made them and thought they tasted intensely like butter, did you maybe use salted butter? It is very important when making meringue buttercreams to use unsalted butter or you end up with something that tastes like sweetened butter... good on a warm scone maybe, but not on a cake. =] I make meringue buttercream all of the time (I make cakes for a living) and it tastes more like vanilla ice cream than butter if you use the unsalted butter. I know not everyone loves meringue based buttercreams, especially American palets since we are used to the overly sweet powdered sugar type buttercreams, but using unsalted butter makes a WORLD of difference. Happy Baking!

