This was so much fun to make, present and eat! For a Saturday birthday party, I actually started the weekend prior. I also doubled the recipe to feed over 20 people which was plenty. First made the cake layers (2 sheets at once) and when cooled, froze them. Then made meringue layers which I wrapped and left out at room temp. On Thursday, made souffle layers. Friday, did buttercreams and assembly. I only increased the buttercream by 30% since reviewers said it was more than enough. This was enough for layers but not for decoration so on Saturday made a quick kahlua buttercm for edging and a chocolate ganache for the birthday writing. Finally, I couldn't resist splashing some kahlua into the simple syrup. Each step isn't so time consuming and I only needed two jelly roll pans. Basically, I couldn't stop, but the raves and hugs and amazement made it so worth it. a special occasion dessert for sure.

Rating: 4
As many bakers said, this is a cake that you needs to take time to make it. I didn't timed myself but it took a few days to make it. I made a few layer ahead of time. However, I had a problem with meringue. Mine become like a sheet of tile so I had to crumble and spread on top of cake and soak with sugar syrup to not to be so crunchy. My cake didn't come out as a picture. It should state in the recipe that it need to be freeze and cut with sharp knife to get a better presentation. Other than that, my crowds raved and compliment that my skill getting to be a pastry chef.

Rating: 4
WOW! My guests loved this. They couldn't believe it was home made. I found the instructions easy to follow. When I make this again, I will prepare all the parts over the course of two or three days, and assemble the day of. We had enough left over to enjoy for the rest of the week, and it kept really well.

Rating: 4
Whew, what a labor of love, but the end result was worth it. I had no difficulty following the instructions even about dusting the cocoa.. I also had the correct pan sizes apparently so the layers were fine. It helps to read through the instructions very carefully once or twice before commencing this endeavor. The other comments were correct about the amount of time. It took me 4.5 - 5 hours. I made it for New Year's Eve in the middle of the day and afternoon and then started dinner after that! I was a little worried when the buttercream curdled, but as the recipe stated, it "came back" and was a good consistency to spread. Very good buttercream but I don't want to think about the calories. I could not find instant espresso powder so I made a regular cup of espresso and used it in the sugar syrupwithout mishap. Then I kept a little bit to use for the espresso syrup wash for the cake layers. The recipe serves more than 12 peopleespecially after a big fancy meal. I would never make this except for a very, very special occasion.

