Rating: 4
I made this for a big family Christmas party and got amazing reviews. It was the only dessert of about 10 items that was completely finished and two guests were literally scraping the serving utensils and the parchment paper for the last bite! It was labour intensive compared to a usual cake but not that much more complicated. It helped to do the cake in several days. I did the cake, souffle and meringue in one day and the buttercreams, syrup and assembly in another. I also agree with another reviewer that the 15" x 10" pan size was odd. I had 12" x 18" pans and ended up splitting the cake into thirds for height so I ended up with more layers. The only caution is to make sure to spread the layers very evenly as the batter spreads very thin and can create an uneven layer after baking. The instructions do seem scattered, but the results are worth it! One reviewer had trouble finding where to put the cocoa powder in the souffle layer, I think it is just dusted on top after the souffle is done. I didn't see where in the instructions to add the salt in the meringue layer but that was pretty easy to figure out. I found it odd that the buttercream recipes make enough for leftovers when it just goes to waste. Next time I would just try to use it all instead of just using the 1/4 cup measure on each layer as suggested. (I even used 1/2 cup measure and still had leftovers) All in all, what a beautiful cake that impresses in looks and taste.

Rating: 4
This was delicious. It got rave reviews from everyone at Christmas dinner. It took me about 6 hours to make. Its very tedious, but not bad if you just plan to do it leisurely. The only problem I had was with the meringue layer. I think it got too crispy. I couldn't get it out in one piece, so I ended up sprinkly crumbled meringue for those layers. It worked fine and still tasted great. The espresso buttercream is so good!

Rating: 3
So. I made this cake and it took a VERY LONG TIME. I like making fussy recipes-i suppose in hopes that it would yield good results. Good- The flavor and presentation is good. I especially like the souffle and the spongecake layers. The merigue buttercream is also very good. it looks complex and the flavors are all very good together. questionable- I didn't fully understand how much the souffle is supposed to deflate. Mine deflated but not all the way (still a bit spongy). It is very hard to transfer during assembly since it so soft and broke at the edges. We patched it up with lots of icing. I don't understand how one should "dry" the meringue layer. i dried it at 350 deg. and it got toasty and almost burnt after 35 min. it did not tell us to turn off the oven.. I'm glad i checked. the dried meringue also posed another problem- it is hard to cut through that layer. I couldn't brush on all the espresso onto the cake because of kids, i lightly brushed. I regret this because i know that the cake is supposed to be moist. I think it is too cold to make this, the icing and the cake did not have a change to meld with each other. I have not done a meringue icing ahead of time before this. i chilled 1 day and brought it back to room temp (still pretty cold though). it is solid hard. i broke it down with the mixer and it broke, but finally came together at the end. wierd. is it just me? the mocha buttercream is harder to re-constitute. i think i overworked it and it came out a bit grainy. no one noticed though. make sure you have the right pan. i used a 9x13 and it came out very tall and we had to eat the cake sideways because the piece would topple over... messy cuts because i can't get through the merigue...

